{"name": "Definition of Arbitrage Pricing Theory (APT)", "@id": "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/apt.asp", "related": ["https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/country-risk-premium.asp", "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/capm.asp", "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/mlr.asp", "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/beta.asp", "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/blackscholes.asp", "https://www.investopedia.com/terms/e/excessreturn.asp"], "body": ["\nArbitrage pricing theory (APT) is a <a data-component=\"link\" data-ordinal=\"1\" data-source=\"inlineLink\" data-type=\"internalLink\" href=\"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/multifactor-model.asp\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">multi-factor</a> asset pricing model based on the idea that an asset's returns can be predicted using the linear relationship between the asset\u2019s expected return and a number of macroeconomic variables that capture systematic risk. It is a useful tool for analyzing portfolios from a <a data-component=\"link\" data-ordinal=\"2\" data-source=\"inlineLink\" data-type=\"internalLink\" href=\"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/v/valueinvesting.asp\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">value investing</a> perspective, in order to identify securities that may be temporarily mispriced.\n", "\n<span data-value=\"\\begin{aligned} &amp;\\text{E(R)}_\\text{i} = E(R)_z + (E(I) - E(R)_z) \\times \\beta_n\\\\ &amp;\\textbf{where:}\\\\ &amp;\\text{E(R)}_\\text{i} = \\text{Expected return on the asset}\\\\ &amp;R_z = \\text{Risk-free rate of return}\\\\ &amp;\\beta_n = \\text{Sensitivity of the asset price to macroeconomic} \\\\ &amp;\\text{factor}\\textit{ n}\\\\ &amp;Ei = \\text{Risk premium associated with factor}\\textit{ i}\\\\ \\end{aligned}\">\ufeff<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\">\n<math>\n<semantics>\n<mrow>\n<mtable>\n<mtr>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow></mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow>\n<mrow></mrow>\n<msub>\n<mtext>\nE(R)\n</mtext>\n<mtext>\ni\n</mtext>\n</msub>\n<mo>\n=\n</mo>\n<mi>\nE\n</mi>\n<mo>\n(\n</mo>\n<mi>\nR\n</mi>\n<msub>\n<mo>\n)\n</mo>\n<mi>\nz\n</mi>\n</msub>\n<mo>\n+\n</mo>\n<mo>\n(\n</mo>\n<mi>\nE\n</mi>\n<mo>\n(\n</mo>\n<mi>\nI\n</mi>\n<mo>\n)\n</mo>\n<mo>\n\u2212\n</mo>\n<mi>\nE\n</mi>\n<mo>\n(\n</mo>\n<mi>\nR\n</mi>\n<msub>\n<mo>\n)\n</mo>\n<mi>\nz\n</mi>\n</msub>\n<mo>\n)\n</mo>\n<mo>\n\u00d7\n</mo>\n<msub>\n<mi>\n\u03b2\n</mi>\n<mi>\nn\n</mi>\n</msub>\n</mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n</mtr>\n<mtr>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow></mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow>\n<mrow></mrow>\n<mtext>\nwhere:\n</mtext>\n</mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n</mtr>\n<mtr>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow></mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow>\n<mrow></mrow>\n<msub>\n<mtext>\nE(R)\n</mtext>\n<mtext>\ni\n</mtext>\n</msub>\n<mo>\n=\n</mo>\n<mtext>\nExpected\u00a0return\u00a0on\u00a0the\u00a0asset\n</mtext>\n</mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n</mtr>\n<mtr>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow></mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow>\n<mrow></mrow>\n<msub>\n<mi>\nR\n</mi>\n<mi>\nz\n</mi>\n</msub>\n<mo>\n=\n</mo>\n<mtext>\nRisk-free\u00a0rate\u00a0of\u00a0return\n</mtext>\n</mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n</mtr>\n<mtr>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow></mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow>\n<mrow></mrow>\n<msub>\n<mi>\n\u03b2\n</mi>\n<mi>\nn\n</mi>\n</msub>\n<mo>\n=\n</mo>\n<mtext>\nSensitivity\u00a0of\u00a0the\u00a0asset\u00a0price\u00a0to\u00a0macroeconomic\n</mtext>\n</mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n</mtr>\n<mtr>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow></mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow>\n<mrow></mrow>\n<mtext>\nfactor\n</mtext>\n<mtext>\n\u00a0n\n</mtext>\n</mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n</mtr>\n<mtr>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow></mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n<mtd>\n<mstyle>\n<mrow>\n<mrow></mrow>\n<mi>\nE\n</mi>\n<mi>\ni\n</mi>\n<mo>\n=\n</mo>\n<mtext>\nRisk\u00a0premium\u00a0associated\u00a0with\u00a0factor\n</mtext>\n<mtext>\n\u00a0i\n</mtext>\n</mrow>\n</mstyle>\n</mtd>\n</mtr>\n</mtable>\n</mrow>\n<annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\n\